    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1947-06-19T19:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1947-06-19T19:00:00-05:00" n="158"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d158">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/6–1247: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Stuart</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1947-06-19T20:00:00-04:00"
                            >June 19, 1947—8 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>749. Coverage by Embassy in its recent telegrams over-all situation China,
                    Manchuria, student unrest and Sinkiang has been great assistance to Dept in
                    following developments. Dept wishes commend Embassy for high calibre its
                    reporting, particularly telegrams nos. 1100 May 20, 1134 May 24,<note n="69"
                        xml:id="d158fn1">Telegram No. 1134 not printed.</note> 1180 May 29, 1235
                    June 7 and 1284 June 12.<note n="70" xml:id="d158fn2">
                        <hi rend="italic">Post</hi>, <ref target="#pg_559">p. 559</ref>.</note>
                    Changchun and Mukden also to be commended for reporting Manchurian
                    situation.</p>
                <p>In this connection Dept would welcome Embassy’s analysis (proposed in Embassy’s
                    1180 May 29) course of action open to US in light probable developments.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
